                <h2>What is Arthritis?</h2>
                <p>Arthritis is an  progressive brain disorder leading to memory loss, cognitive decline, and changes in behavior.
                    It affects the brain's ability to process information, ultimately impacting a person's ability to perform daily tasks independently.</p>
                    <br><br><h3>Causes and Risk Factors:</h3>
                    <p>Age is the primary risk factor, with the likelihood of developing the disease increasing significantly after the age of 65.
                        Genetic factors, such as specific gene mutations and family history, can play a role in its development.
                        Other risk factors include a history of head trauma, cardiovascular conditions, and lifestyle factors like smoking and obesity.                    </p>
                   
                    <h3>Symptoms:</h3>
                    <p>Early symptoms include difficulty remembering recent conversations, names, or events, and mild cognitive impairment.
                        As the disease progresses, individuals may experience confusion, disorientation, mood swings, and difficulty speaking, swallowing, and walking.                   
                    <h3>Treatment Options:                    </h3>
                    <p>Medications like cholinesterase inhibitors (donepezil, rivastigmine, and galantamine) and memantine can help manage cognitive symptoms and improve quality of life.
                        Non-pharmacological interventions, such as cognitive stimulation, physical exercise, and social engagement, may slow the progression of symptoms.
                        Caregiver education and support are essential for understanding the disease's trajectory and providing optimal care.</p>
                  
                    
                    <h3>Long-Term Management:                    </h3>
                    <p>Regular monitoring and assessment of cognitive and functional abilities to facilitate appropriate care planning and adjustments.
                        Creating a safe and supportive environment for the individual, including modifications to the living environment and ensuring adequate supervision.
                        Support groups and community resources can offer emotional support and practical assistance for caregivers and families coping with the challenges of caring for individuals with Alzheimer's disease.
                        Collaborative care involving neurologists, geriatricians, mental health professionals, and caregivers is crucial for providing comprehensive and holistic management of the condition, ensuring the best possible quality of life for those affected.
                        
                        
                        
                        
